[[Ernest Benn Limited]]’s '''''Sixpenny Library''''' is a complete series of reference books published in the late 1920s and early 1930s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.publishinghistory.com/benns-sixpenny-library.html|title=Benn's Sixpenny Library (Ernest Benn Limited) - Book Series List|website=www.publishinghistory.com|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref>.  The library included over one hundred and eighty volumes.  The series was edited by [[Bill Rose (editor)|William Rose]], who solicited current authorities in such areas as history, literature, religion, psychology, science, and economics.  Some contributing authors were [[Hilaire Belloc]], [[Maurice Baring]], [[J.B. Priestley]], Sir (later Lord) [[Robert Baden-Powell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/131820238627|title=Scouting and Youth Movements by Sir Robert Baden Powell 1929 Benn's Sixpenny   - eBay|website=eBay}}</ref>, [[Sir Oliver Lodge]], [[S.V. Keeling|S.V Keeling]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/logic-and-reasoning/oclc/14205637|title=Logic and reasoning|last=Keeling|first=S. V|date=1929|publisher=Ernest Benn Ltd.|location=London|language=English}}</ref> and [[Sir Ernest Benn]] himself. ''[[The Spectator]]'', in November 1927, after announcing some the latest additions to "Messrs Benn's excellent Sixpenny Library"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/5th-november-1927/21/messrs-benns-excellent-sixpenny-library-has-recent|title=Messrs. Benn's excellent Sixpenny Library has recently issued the following » 5 Nov 1927 » The Spectator Archive|work=The Spectator Archive|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> devoted a further paragraph to his contribution on Trade<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/5th-november-1927/21/what-does-a-normal-man-do-in-a-normal-day|title=What does a normal man do in a normal day » 5 Nov 1927 » The Spectator Archive|work=The Spectator Archive|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> (both of which are free to read online). Partial lists of the books published in the series can be found [http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=se%3A%22Benn%27s+sixpenny+library%22&fq=&dblist=638&qt=sort&se=yr&sd=asc&qt=sort_yr_asc here] and [http://www.publishinghistory.com/benns-sixpenny-library.html here].

The books were praised by critics for their excellence, brevity, and inexpensive price.

